cs.CV, cs.LG, cs.MM, cs.AI, cs.NE 

The paper focuses on improving the efficiency of video action recognition, which is a task related to computer vision (CV). Therefore, cs.CV is the most likely sub-category. The paper also proposes a dynamic inference approach that involves optimizing the network depth and the number of input video frames, which is a machine learning (ML) problem. Hence, cs.LG is also a likely sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves modeling the temporal relation of videos, which is a multimedia (MM) problem, making cs.MM another possible sub-category. The paper also uses a prediction module and an online temporal shift module, which are AI techniques, making cs.AI a likely sub-category. Finally, the paper involves optimizing the inference process, which is a neural and evolutionary computing (NE) problem, making cs.NE a possible sub-category.
